00:41:58.780 --> 00:42:02.940 align:middle line:84%
on the inception of a radio,
a simple little radio.

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:05.044 align:middle line:90%
Let's show that clip.

00:42:05.044 --> 00:42:05.960 align:middle line:90%
[START VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:08.418 align:middle line:10%
>>I was walking to work and I
wanted to listen to the news.

00:42:08.418 --> 00:42:11.960 align:middle line:10%
I found this cute little
green radio for $4.99.

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:13.880 align:middle line:10%
I was standing there in
line to buy this thing

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:17.750 align:middle line:10%
and I was thinking, how
could $4.99 possibly capture

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:21.430 align:middle line:10%
the costs of making this radio
and getting it into my hands?

00:42:21.430 --> 00:42:23.720 align:middle line:84%
The metal was probably
mined in South Africa,

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:26.090 align:middle line:84%
the petroleum was
probably drilled in Iraq,

00:42:26.090 --> 00:42:28.330 align:middle line:84%
the plastics were probably
produced in China,

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:31.600 align:middle line:84%
and maybe the whole thing
was assembled in Mexico.

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:34.080 align:middle line:84%
$4.99 wouldn't even pay the
rent for the shelf space

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:36.550 align:middle line:84%
it occupied until I came
along, let alone part

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:38.870 align:middle line:84%
of the staff guy's salary
who helped me pick it out

00:42:38.870 --> 00:42:40.960 align:middle line:84%
or the multiple ocean
cruises and truck

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:43.170 align:middle line:84%
rides pieces of
this radio went on.

00:42:43.170 --> 00:42:46.690 align:middle line:84%
That's how I realized I
didn't pay for the radio.

00:42:46.690 --> 00:42:47.900 align:middle line:90%
So who did pay?

00:42:47.900 --> 00:42:50.930 align:middle line:84%
Well, these people paid with the
loss of their natural resource

00:42:50.930 --> 00:42:51.750 align:middle line:90%
space.

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:54.180 align:middle line:84%
These people paid with the
loss of their clean air,

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:56.370 align:middle line:84%
with increasing asthma
and cancer rates.

00:42:56.370 --> 00:42:58.980 align:middle line:84%
All along this system,
people pitched in

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:01.690 align:middle line:84%
so I could get this
radio for $4.99.

00:43:01.690 --> 00:43:02.950 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:43:02.950 --> 00:43:04.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love that
because it really

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:07.272 align:middle line:84%
made it in a very simple
term-- the beginning, middle,

00:43:07.272 --> 00:43:08.480 align:middle line:90%
and end-- of where things go.

00:43:08.480 --> 00:43:10.313 align:middle line:84%
And it makes you think
more consciously when

00:43:10.313 --> 00:43:13.010 align:middle line:84%
you're in a place,
being a consumer.

00:43:13.010 --> 00:43:14.140 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

00:43:14.140 --> 00:43:16.980 align:middle line:84%
I must say, that
is a 20 minute film

00:43:16.980 --> 00:43:18.390 align:middle line:90%
called "The Story of Stuff"--

00:43:18.390 --> 00:43:19.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:24.060 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --by an incredible
activist named Annie Leonard.

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:27.380 align:middle line:84%
And all of her things are
great. "Story of Stuff"

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:28.630 align:middle line:90%
has won all kinds of awards.

00:43:28.630 --> 00:43:30.770 align:middle line:84%
But I recommend people go
look at the whole thing

00:43:30.770 --> 00:43:35.350 align:middle line:84%
because you'll see, really,
the story of our stuff.

00:43:35.350 --> 00:43:37.290 align:middle line:84%
And we just don't
think about it.

00:43:37.290 --> 00:43:39.840 align:middle line:84%
And when you find out about
it, when you learn about it,

00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:42.020 align:middle line:84%
then you start being
much more discerning.

00:43:42.020 --> 00:43:43.560 align:middle line:90%
And it enriches your life.

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:44.879 align:middle line:90%
You give up nothing.

00:43:44.879 --> 00:43:46.670 align:middle line:84%
The main thing I want
to say is that people

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:47.710 align:middle line:84%
get afraid they're
going to have to give up

00:43:47.710 --> 00:43:48.584 align:middle line:90%
the things they love.

00:43:48.584 --> 00:43:49.350 align:middle line:90%
They don't.

00:43:49.350 --> 00:43:52.410 align:middle line:84%
They'll end up loving the
things they have way more.

00:43:52.410 --> 00:43:55.510 align:middle line:84%
I remember-- there's a
great quote from Aristotle.

00:43:55.510 --> 00:43:58.600 align:middle line:84%
He said, I love to
go to the market

00:43:58.600 --> 00:44:01.510 align:middle line:84%
to see all the
things I don't need.

00:44:01.510 --> 00:44:03.610 align:middle line:84%
And it's kind of like,
you start to realize, God,

00:44:03.610 --> 00:44:05.280 align:middle line:84%
I've got everything
I need and I'm

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:06.680 align:middle line:84%
going to do a
better job with it.

00:44:06.680 --> 00:44:09.770 align:middle line:84%
And it makes your life
richer rather than poorer.

00:44:09.770 --> 00:44:11.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And the
indigenous people

00:44:11.190 --> 00:44:13.900 align:middle line:84%
don't have that attachment
to stuff, and even money.

00:44:13.900 --> 00:44:17.090 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And it makes their
life much richer, frankly,

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:19.890 align:middle line:84%
much more meaningful,
less cluttered,

00:44:19.890 --> 00:44:21.970 align:middle line:90%
and their mind clear.

