And so I just want
people to know

00:44:24.020 --> 00:44:25.720 align:middle line:84%
they don't do give
almost anything up.

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:30.840 align:middle line:84%
It's what they'll gain is really
what the power of all this is.

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:33.747 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it declutters
and uncomplicates things.

00:44:33.747 --> 00:44:34.330 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

00:44:34.330 --> 00:44:36.205 align:middle line:84%
You know how good you
feel when you clear out

00:44:36.205 --> 00:44:38.280 align:middle line:84%
your closet, for example,
or clean out a drawer?

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:41.010 align:middle line:84%
It's like doing that
with the way you live.

00:44:41.010 --> 00:44:45.150 align:middle line:84%
And if we can do
that as a society,

00:44:45.150 --> 00:44:47.034 align:middle line:84%
I can't tell you how
great it's going to be.

00:44:47.034 --> 00:44:48.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It also
helps to declutter

00:44:48.450 --> 00:44:50.229 align:middle line:84%
your mind and your
attachment to things.

00:44:50.229 --> 00:44:50.770 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yes.

00:44:50.770 --> 00:44:52.220 align:middle line:84%
And all our doubts
about ourselves--

00:44:52.220 --> 00:44:52.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All that stuff.

00:44:52.680 --> 00:44:53.846 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: --all that chatter.

00:44:53.846 --> 00:44:54.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:44:54.750 --> 00:44:55.000 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:56.150 align:middle line:84%
We're going to
take a quick break.

00:44:56.150 --> 00:44:58.191 align:middle line:84%
When we come back, we're
going to talk about some

00:44:58.191 --> 00:45:01.170 align:middle line:84%
of the prophecies that the
indigenous cultures have

00:45:01.170 --> 00:45:01.800 align:middle line:90%
taught you.

00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:04.620 align:middle line:84%
And you could share that
with around this culmination

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:07.070 align:middle line:84%
of this 2012 date and
some of the journeys

00:45:07.070 --> 00:45:07.950 align:middle line:90%
that you've been on.

00:45:07.950 --> 00:45:08.380 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Great.

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:08.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All right.

00:45:08.680 --> 00:45:09.513 align:middle line:90%
We'll be right back.

00:45:09.513 --> 00:45:10.386 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Thank you.

00:45:10.386 --> 00:45:11.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Welcome back.

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:13.820 align:middle line:84%
I'm Lisa Garr and I'm
joined by Lynne Twist who

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:18.430 align:middle line:84%
is a true global activist and
an inspiration to many of us.

00:45:18.430 --> 00:45:21.930 align:middle line:84%
So we were talking about
the indigenous cultures

00:45:21.930 --> 00:45:22.730 align:middle line:90%
that you visited.

00:45:22.730 --> 00:45:27.450 align:middle line:84%
And what is their perspective
around this coming of the 2012,

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:30.027 align:middle line:84%
the end of time, the
beginning of a new cycle?

00:45:30.027 --> 00:45:31.860 align:middle line:84%
Can you share with us
some of the prophecies

00:45:31.860 --> 00:45:32.680 align:middle line:90%
that you've heard?

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:34.180 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Well, one
of the prophecies

00:45:34.180 --> 00:45:35.820 align:middle line:84%
that I'm most
familiar with-- now,

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:39.460 align:middle line:84%
everybody knows that the Mayan
prophecy or the Mayan calendar

00:45:39.460 --> 00:45:40.740 align:middle line:90%
ends in 2012.

00:45:40.740 --> 00:45:43.400 align:middle line:84%
And that's a very,
very significant thing

00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:45.840 align:middle line:84%
for the Mayan people,
obviously, and also

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:48.560 align:middle line:84%
indigenous people around the
world are pretty aware of that.

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:50.600 align:middle line:84%
And so if you think
about the Mayans,

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:54.160 align:middle line:84%
they've been kind of waiting
for 2012 for 2,000 years

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:55.110 align:middle line:90%
or thousands of years.

00:45:55.110 --> 00:45:55.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:45:55.440 --> 00:45:57.356 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: So it's something
to pay attention to

00:45:57.356 --> 00:45:59.380 align:middle line:90%
even if you don't buy it.

00:45:59.380 --> 00:46:01.000 align:middle line:84%
The prophecy I'm
most familiar with

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.410 align:middle line:84%
is the prophecy of the
eagle and the condor.

00:46:03.410 --> 00:46:05.660 align:middle line:84%
And the indigenous peoples
of the Amazon and the Andes

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:07.310 align:middle line:84%
have been telling
it for millennia.

00:46:07.310 --> 00:46:08.870 align:middle line:10%
I mean, really,
thousands of years

00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:10.550 align:middle line:10%
about this time in history.

00:46:10.550 --> 00:46:13.640 align:middle line:10%
And it comes to fruition
right about now.

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:17.290 align:middle line:10%
And 2012 is an important
milestone in that prophecy.

00:46:17.290 --> 00:46:20.540 align:middle line:10%
And that prophecy says that
at this time in history

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:24.120 align:middle line:10%
the eagle people, who are
the people who perceive life

00:46:24.120 --> 00:46:27.550 align:middle line:10%
primarily through the mind--
that's people like us--

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:32.020 align:middle line:10%
will have reached a zenith in
their capacity to use the mind.

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:35.090 align:middle line:84%
In fact, they will have
even invented tools

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:37.681 align:middle line:84%
to extend the
capacity of the mind.

00:46:37.681 --> 00:46:39.930 align:middle line:84%
That's probably the computer
and the smartphones and--

00:46:39.930 --> 00:46:40.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Technology age.

00:46:40.260 --> 00:46:42.200 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --and all
that stuff we've got.

00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:44.850 align:middle line:84%
And they will be
material rich beyond

00:46:44.850 --> 00:46:47.800 align:middle line:84%
any previous
generation's imagination,

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:51.360 align:middle line:84%
but they will be spiritually
impoverished to their peril

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:54.550 align:middle line:84%
and their very survival
will be at risk.

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:57.200 align:middle line:84%
While the condor people,
and the condor people

00:46:57.200 --> 00:46:59.900 align:middle line:84%
refers to the indigenous
peoples of the planet,

00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:02.860 align:middle line:84%
people who live primarily
through the wisdom of the heart

00:47:02.860 --> 00:47:05.920 align:middle line:84%
and perceive life
through the five senses.

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:09.360 align:middle line:84%
Those-- and are very conversant
with the spirit world.

00:47:09.360 --> 00:47:12.730 align:middle line:84%
The condor people will be
at an incredible zenith

00:47:12.730 --> 00:47:17.180 align:middle line:84%
in their capacity to
intuitive skills and instinct

00:47:17.180 --> 00:47:20.080 align:middle line:84%
and understanding their
kin in the natural world

00:47:20.080 --> 00:47:23.630 align:middle line:84%
and the natural world
cycles and the spirit world.

00:47:23.630 --> 00:47:27.500 align:middle line:84%
Yet, they will be
materially impoverished

00:47:27.500 --> 00:47:30.390 align:middle line:84%
to their peril in any
encounter with the eagle world

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:32.532 align:middle line:84%
and their very survival
will be a risk.

00:47:32.532 --> 00:47:34.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's a
shadow to each side.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:34.781 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yes.

00:47:34.781 --> 00:47:38.220 align:middle line:84%
And both sides will
be at their zenith.

00:47:38.220 --> 00:47:40.650 align:middle line:84%
And that in this last
500 year period, which is

00:47:40.650 --> 00:47:42.150 align:middle line:84%
called a Pachacuti,
which was called

00:47:42.150 --> 00:47:44.610 align:middle line:84%
the Pachacuti of
dominance and darkness

00:47:44.610 --> 00:47:47.240 align:middle line:90%
which began right around 1492.

00:47:47.240 --> 00:47:48.740 align:middle line:90%
That sounds familiar.

00:47:48.740 --> 00:47:52.830 align:middle line:84%
500 years of dominance and
darkness by the eagle people.

00:47:52.830 --> 00:47:55.160 align:middle line:84%
The condor people
and the eagle people

00:47:55.160 --> 00:47:57.790 align:middle line:84%
and the beginning of
this next 500 year cycle,

00:47:57.790 --> 00:48:00.810 align:middle line:84%
which is called the
tenth Pachacutec,

00:48:00.810 --> 00:48:02.770 align:middle line:84%
is the Pachacutec of
balance and light.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:06.550 align:middle line:84%
And this is when the
eagle and the condor

00:48:06.550 --> 00:48:09.470 align:middle line:84%
will remember that
they are each other

00:48:09.470 --> 00:48:13.370 align:middle line:84%
and reunite, remember,
and fly together

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:16.540 align:middle line:84%
in the same skies, wing to
wing, and the whole world

00:48:16.540 --> 00:48:19.240 align:middle line:84%
will come back into
balance for 500 years.

00:48:19.240 --> 00:48:20.690 align:middle line:84%
That's the prophecy
for this time.

00:48:20.690 --> 00:48:23.520 align:middle line:84%
And they say that
the 25 years where

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:26.750 align:middle line:84%
we move from one Pachacutec,
one 500 year cycle,

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:29.380 align:middle line:84%
to the next 500
year cycle, there

00:48:29.380 --> 00:48:33.020 align:middle line:84%
will be a humbling of all
the creatures of the Earth

00:48:33.020 --> 00:48:35.170 align:middle line:90%
by Pachamama herself.

00:48:35.170 --> 00:48:39.220 align:middle line:84%
That is tsunamis, earthquakes,
volcanic eruptions,

00:48:39.220 --> 00:48:43.660 align:middle line:84%
tidal waves, unexpected
climate changes.

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:47.010 align:middle line:84%
They've been prophesying this
really for thousands of years.

00:48:47.010 --> 00:48:50.430 align:middle line:84%
And that's Pachamama
humbling her creatures

00:48:50.430 --> 00:48:53.820 align:middle line:84%
so they will find their rightful
relationship with her as we

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:56.730 align:middle line:84%
go into the Pachacutec
of balance and light

00:48:56.730 --> 00:48:59.520 align:middle line:84%
and the eagle and the condor
fly together in the same sky.

00:48:59.520 --> 00:49:01.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That resonates so much.

00:49:01.110 --> 00:49:02.360 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: I love that prophecy.

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:03.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So much.

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:05.110 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: It's so positive.

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:06.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But it's not
just that culture.

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:08.320 align:middle line:84%
It's many different
cultures that

00:49:08.320 --> 00:49:10.930 align:middle line:84%
have had similar
types of prophecies.

00:49:10.930 --> 00:49:11.930 align:middle line:90%
The White Buffalo.

00:49:11.930 --> 00:49:13.030 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: The White
Buffalo prophecy

00:49:13.030 --> 00:49:14.863 align:middle line:84%
is coming to fruition
from the native people

00:49:14.863 --> 00:49:16.800 align:middle line:84%
of the Americas,
the North Americans.

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:19.210 align:middle line:84%
The Hopi prophecy,
we are the ones

00:49:19.210 --> 00:49:21.210 align:middle line:84%
we've been waiting for
which is quoted so often

00:49:21.210 --> 00:49:23.820 align:middle line:90%
is coming to fruition 2012.

00:49:23.820 --> 00:49:26.730 align:middle line:84%
The eagle and the condor
prophecy, the Mayan prophecy,

00:49:26.730 --> 00:49:29.930 align:middle line:84%
and I've learned
from Terence McKenna,

00:49:29.930 --> 00:49:34.200 align:middle line:84%
the great ethnobotanist who's no
longer living, but in a session

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:36.840 align:middle line:84%
we had with him, that
the "I Ching" even

00:49:36.840 --> 00:49:38.860 align:middle line:90%
has a prophecy about 2012.

00:49:38.860 --> 00:49:41.950 align:middle line:84%
And that prophecy says
we're ending thousands

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:44.920 align:middle line:84%
of years of a culture
of habit and we

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:48.430 align:middle line:84%
move into a culture
of novelty, is the way

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:50.370 align:middle line:84%
that-- that the "I
Ching" talks about it.

00:49:50.370 --> 00:49:53.070 align:middle line:84%
So all of these prophecies
coming to fruition

00:49:53.070 --> 00:49:56.010 align:middle line:84%
at the same time
makes 2012, I think,

00:49:56.010 --> 00:50:00.120 align:middle line:84%
a year of beauty, magic, and
transformation for all of us.

00:50:00.120 --> 00:50:04.150 align:middle line:84%
Even if you don't buy any
of that stuff, or if you do,

00:50:04.150 --> 00:50:06.940 align:middle line:84%
thousands and
thousands of years ago,

00:50:06.940 --> 00:50:08.770 align:middle line:90%
people were talking about 2012.

00:50:08.770 --> 00:50:10.840 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
to pay attention to.

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:12.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a very
significant time in history.

00:50:12.910 --> 00:50:15.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's not the
Hollywood end of times

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:17.070 align:middle line:90%
that we see the movies about.

00:50:17.070 --> 00:50:19.370 align:middle line:84%
This is something that
has been prophesied

00:50:19.370 --> 00:50:21.260 align:middle line:90%
by many different cultures.

00:50:21.260 --> 00:50:23.680 align:middle line:84%
I look at it is
something where it

00:50:23.680 --> 00:50:25.630 align:middle line:84%
is what you believe
it to be as well.

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:28.160 align:middle line:84%
You can make it as positive
as you want it to be.

00:50:28.160 --> 00:50:30.340 align:middle line:84%
You could make it
a time for growth.

00:50:30.340 --> 00:50:34.360 align:middle line:84%
I've heard different
astrological forecasts

00:50:34.360 --> 00:50:36.030 align:middle line:84%
of planetary alignments
and so forth.

00:50:36.030 --> 00:50:38.810 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's whatever
your belief system is.

00:50:38.810 --> 00:50:43.150 align:middle line:84%
But it also can relate to
what you put into the future.

00:50:43.150 --> 00:50:47.177 align:middle line:84%
I've heard that the seeds
planted in 2011 grow in 2012.

00:50:47.177 --> 00:50:48.510 align:middle line:90%
It's all these different things.

00:50:48.510 --> 00:50:50.215 align:middle line:84%
But you catch what
you want to hear--

00:50:50.215 --> 00:50:50.840 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Right.

00:50:50.840 --> 00:50:53.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --and as long as
it serves you and humanity,

00:50:53.820 --> 00:50:55.247 align:middle line:90%
it's fine with me.

00:50:55.247 --> 00:50:55.830 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

00:50:55.830 --> 00:50:56.910 align:middle line:90%
I agree with that.

00:50:56.910 --> 00:50:59.300 align:middle line:84%
And many people-- like
Barbara Marx Hubbard

00:50:59.300 --> 00:51:02.080 align:middle line:84%
is orchestrating this
whole birthday 2012.

00:51:02.080 --> 00:51:03.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:51:03.440 --> 00:51:07.060 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: The Mayan prophecy
calendar ends on December 21,

00:51:07.060 --> 00:51:09.995 align:middle line:84%
and December 22 she's
calling the birthday.

00:51:09.995 --> 00:51:10.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's great.

00:51:10.870 --> 00:51:12.720 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And I would
say that it's a time--

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:15.230 align:middle line:84%
and really speaking of people
making a difference with

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:17.470 align:middle line:84%
their life and getting
on some sort of a path--

00:51:17.470 --> 00:51:18.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Getting into
action about it.

00:51:18.570 --> 00:51:19.778 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Getting into action.

00:51:19.778 --> 00:51:21.790 align:middle line:84%
One way of looking at
our time in history

00:51:21.790 --> 00:51:23.650 align:middle line:84%
is that we are
alive at a time when

00:51:23.650 --> 00:51:28.050 align:middle line:84%
we can hospice the death of
the old structures, cultures

00:51:28.050 --> 00:51:30.690 align:middle line:84%
and systems that really
no longer serve us.

00:51:30.690 --> 00:51:32.470 align:middle line:90%
And we can hospice their death.

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:33.680 align:middle line:90%
We don't need to kill them.

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:35.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That are breaking
down all around us.

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:35.683 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

00:51:35.683 --> 00:51:37.490 align:middle line:90%
Because they are dying.

00:51:37.490 --> 00:51:39.040 align:middle line:84%
If they're
unsustainable that means

00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:42.190 align:middle line:84%
they can't last so
they are falling apart.

00:51:42.190 --> 00:51:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And if we hospice
their natural death,

00:51:44.910 --> 00:51:47.130 align:middle line:84%
they'll die faster
and more gracefully.

00:51:47.130 --> 00:51:50.660 align:middle line:84%
While we midwife the birth of
the new structures and systems

00:51:50.660 --> 00:51:52.990 align:middle line:84%
that are appropriate,
that are awakened,

00:51:52.990 --> 00:51:54.500 align:middle line:84%
that are appropriate
to a long term

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:56.150 align:middle line:90%
future for the human family.

00:51:56.150 --> 00:51:58.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the breaking
down of old systems

00:51:58.380 --> 00:52:00.305 align:middle line:84%
has basically been
prophesied and that's

00:52:00.305 --> 00:52:02.430 align:middle line:84%
kind of what we're
experiencing, what we're seeing.

00:52:02.430 --> 00:52:02.971 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yes.

00:52:02.971 --> 00:52:06.650 align:middle line:84%
You could say that this comes
from the great ecologist

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:10.410 align:middle line:84%
and businessman and speaker
and just a hero for me,

00:52:10.410 --> 00:52:11.150 align:middle line:90%
Paul Hawken.

00:52:11.150 --> 00:52:16.111 align:middle line:84%
He says that our species'
immune system is kicking him.

00:52:16.111 --> 00:52:16.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:52:16.610 --> 00:52:17.950 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: And I just love that.

00:52:17.950 --> 00:52:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And you can see the
Occupy Movements

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:23.550 align:middle line:84%
now-- it's in 50 cities and it's
in 67 countries or maybe more

00:52:23.550 --> 00:52:24.220 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:52:24.220 --> 00:52:25.380 align:middle line:90%
And it's like an immune system--

00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:27.088 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, if you
look at it on a map.

00:52:27.088 --> 00:52:32.030 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --really designed to
heal environmental degradation,

00:52:32.030 --> 00:52:35.740 align:middle line:84%
political corruption,
the kinds of things

00:52:35.740 --> 00:52:39.260 align:middle line:84%
that come from ideologies that
we've sort of gotten addicted

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:40.930 align:middle line:84%
to that no longer
make a difference

00:52:40.930 --> 00:52:44.330 align:middle line:84%
and are actually inappropriate
and dishonest now.

00:52:44.330 --> 00:52:46.620 align:middle line:84%
For a world that
knows that it needs

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:48.151 align:middle line:90%
to really transform and change.

00:52:48.151 --> 00:52:50.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I've noticed that
on a personal level as well.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:52.890 align:middle line:84%
On my radio show, people
are calling in talking about

00:52:52.890 --> 00:52:57.540 align:middle line:84%
relationships breaking down,
old jobs breaking down,

00:52:57.540 --> 00:53:01.160 align:middle line:84%
even family systems breaking
down that really were

00:53:01.160 --> 00:53:05.000 align:middle line:84%
in the old paradigm and no
longer able to be sustained now

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:08.650 align:middle line:84%
because the energy has shifted,
the consciousness has shifted,

00:53:08.650 --> 00:53:11.790 align:middle line:84%
it has reached a point of
critical mass where those

00:53:11.790 --> 00:53:15.330 align:middle line:84%
systems cannot exist any longer
because who we are being has

00:53:15.330 --> 00:53:16.195 align:middle line:90%
shifted so much.

00:53:16.195 --> 00:53:16.820 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Right.

00:53:16.820 --> 00:53:17.940 align:middle line:90%
And they're not bad.

00:53:17.940 --> 00:53:20.460 align:middle line:84%
They were of service,
but they're not relevant

00:53:20.460 --> 00:53:20.960 align:middle line:90%
any longer.

00:53:20.960 --> 00:53:21.751 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Any longer.

00:53:21.751 --> 00:53:24.970 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: So it's really like--
I like to actually even put

00:53:24.970 --> 00:53:27.966 align:middle line:84%
the financial turn
down, downturn--

00:53:27.966 --> 00:53:29.590 align:middle line:84%
turn down, that's
what you do to a bed.

00:53:29.590 --> 00:53:30.090 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:53:30.090 --> 00:53:33.600 align:middle line:84%
Downturn or what's often
called the financial crisis

00:53:33.600 --> 00:53:34.860 align:middle line:90%
in that context as well.

00:53:34.860 --> 00:53:37.630 align:middle line:84%
Because I see it-- and I
do a lot of work with money

00:53:37.630 --> 00:53:40.620 align:middle line:84%
as you know as a fundraiser and
a philanthropist and someone

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:43.240 align:middle line:84%
who works with
money, and I know we

00:53:43.240 --> 00:53:48.530 align:middle line:84%
want to talk about that
too-- as a huge purification.

00:53:48.530 --> 00:53:53.390 align:middle line:84%
This financial quote unquote
crisis that began in 2007, 2008

00:53:53.390 --> 00:53:54.400 align:middle line:90%
is such a blessing.

00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:55.960 align:middle line:90%
Now, it's painful.

00:53:55.960 --> 00:53:57.080 align:middle line:90%
Oh, my God, it's painful.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:53:59.640 align:middle line:84%
People have lost their
homes and their retirement

00:53:59.640 --> 00:54:01.500 align:middle line:90%
and all kinds of--

00:54:01.500 --> 00:54:03.370 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How are you
calling it a blessing?

00:54:03.370 --> 00:54:07.050 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Because we as
a-- if you look long view,

00:54:07.050 --> 00:54:11.040 align:middle line:84%
not short view-- we really
need to wake up about money.

00:54:11.040 --> 00:54:15.680 align:middle line:84%
We need to really have almost
like a shamanic shape shift

00:54:15.680 --> 00:54:17.690 align:middle line:90%
purification about money.

00:54:17.690 --> 00:54:21.300 align:middle line:84%
We need to come to
terms with the way

00:54:21.300 --> 00:54:23.540 align:middle line:84%
that we've gotten
caught and lost

00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:24.950 align:middle line:90%
in our relationship with money.

00:54:24.950 --> 00:54:27.820 align:middle line:84%
And money is really
just a symbol

00:54:27.820 --> 00:54:32.360 align:middle line:84%
in many ways of the lost
soul of our species.

00:54:32.360 --> 00:54:36.380 align:middle line:84%
But we've really gotten caught
in our relationship with money.

00:54:36.380 --> 00:54:38.690 align:middle line:84%
And so the financial
crisis, you could

00:54:38.690 --> 00:54:42.470 align:middle line:84%
call it a cleansing, a
purification, an opportunity

00:54:42.470 --> 00:54:46.060 align:middle line:84%
to reboot, to
rethink, to resource,

00:54:46.060 --> 00:54:50.140 align:middle line:84%
reinvent our relationship with
ourselves, the natural world,

00:54:50.140 --> 00:54:53.460 align:middle line:84%
each other and put
money in its place

00:54:53.460 --> 00:54:56.200 align:middle line:84%
rather than right here in
front of every human being

00:54:56.200 --> 00:54:58.450 align:middle line:84%
and being the only thing
they care about and the thing

00:54:58.450 --> 00:55:01.980 align:middle line:84%
they eclipse everything else
in order to get their hands on.

00:55:01.980 --> 00:55:04.490 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what is the new
relationship with money?

00:55:04.490 --> 00:55:06.090 align:middle line:90%
What does that look like?

00:55:06.090 --> 00:55:08.534 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Well, in this book,
which is sitting right here.

00:55:08.534 --> 00:55:09.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: "The Soul of Money."

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:10.930 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: "The Soul of Money."

00:55:10.930 --> 00:55:12.180 align:middle line:90%
Which I wrote.

00:55:12.180 --> 00:55:14.900 align:middle line:84%
And I wrote it-- I wrote
it a long time ago.

00:55:14.900 --> 00:55:19.720 align:middle line:84%
Actually, it seems like a long
time ago, it came out in 2004--

00:55:19.720 --> 00:55:21.400 align:middle line:90%
the end of 2003, 2004.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:23.660 align:middle line:84%
But it's more
relevant now than ever

00:55:23.660 --> 00:55:30.220 align:middle line:84%
because in that conversation
I really examine

00:55:30.220 --> 00:55:35.850 align:middle line:84%
what I call the lie of scarcity
or the condition of scarcity.

00:55:35.850 --> 00:55:38.650 align:middle line:84%
Which is really haunts
the human family.

00:55:38.650 --> 00:55:42.170 align:middle line:84%
A belief, an unconscious,
unexamined assumption--

00:55:42.170 --> 00:55:45.720 align:middle line:84%
and just to go back
to that-- we have

00:55:45.720 --> 00:55:48.525 align:middle line:84%
unconscious, unexamined
assumptions about money that

00:55:48.525 --> 00:55:50.950 align:middle line:84%
are literally
choking us to death.

00:55:50.950 --> 00:55:54.470 align:middle line:84%
And first of all, we
forget that we invented it.

00:55:54.470 --> 00:55:55.870 align:middle line:90%
We made money up.

00:55:55.870 --> 00:55:58.580 align:middle line:84%
It's our creation, it
doesn't grow on trees,

00:55:58.580 --> 00:56:00.230 align:middle line:90%
pennies do not rain from heaven.

00:56:00.230 --> 00:56:03.930 align:middle line:84%
We invented money, only
about 3,500, 4,500 years ago.

00:56:03.930 --> 00:56:05.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: As a means of--

00:56:05.390 --> 00:56:08.750 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And for the purpose of
facilitating sharing with one

00:56:08.750 --> 00:56:09.250 align:middle line:90%
other--

00:56:09.250 --> 00:56:09.833 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Trade.

00:56:09.833 --> 00:56:11.310 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --our
goods and services.

00:56:11.310 --> 00:56:15.770 align:middle line:84%
And that purpose for money
has-- we've lost sight of that.

00:56:15.770 --> 00:56:17.770 align:middle line:84%
We now exchange
goods and services

00:56:17.770 --> 00:56:20.810 align:middle line:84%
so that we can have money
rather than use money

00:56:20.810 --> 00:56:25.170 align:middle line:84%
to facilitate the equanimity,
the goods and service exchange

00:56:25.170 --> 00:56:26.852 align:middle line:84%
from human beings
to one another.

00:56:26.852 --> 00:56:28.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And once again,
become detached from it

00:56:28.810 --> 00:56:30.110 align:middle line:90%
with the plastic and the paper.

00:56:30.110 --> 00:56:30.200 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

00:56:30.200 --> 00:56:30.540 align:middle line:90%
Oh, my God.

00:56:30.540 --> 00:56:31.120 align:middle line:90%
It's insane.

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:32.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's numbers now.

00:56:32.780 --> 00:56:34.440 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And we
used to be citizens

00:56:34.440 --> 00:56:36.220 align:middle line:84%
and now we're not
even called citizens.

00:56:36.220 --> 00:56:37.400 align:middle line:90%
We're called consumers.

00:56:37.400 --> 00:56:39.149 align:middle line:84%
And if you look that
up in the dictionary,

00:56:39.149 --> 00:56:41.330 align:middle line:84%
it's the most unattractive
word for a human being.

00:56:41.330 --> 00:56:44.970 align:middle line:84%
It means he or she who
takes, depletes, diminishes,

00:56:44.970 --> 00:56:45.552 align:middle line:90%
or destroys.

00:56:45.552 --> 00:56:46.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Consumer?

00:56:46.260 --> 00:56:47.430 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: That's what
the word consumer means.

00:56:47.430 --> 00:56:48.638 align:middle line:90%
That's what we're called now.

00:56:48.638 --> 00:56:50.420 align:middle line:90%
We named ourselves that.

00:56:50.420 --> 00:56:52.420 align:middle line:84%
And the word citizen,
on the other hand,

00:56:52.420 --> 00:56:55.360 align:middle line:84%
means he or she who
stands for the well being

00:56:55.360 --> 00:56:58.620 align:middle line:84%
of the community, the state,
the nation or the world.

00:56:58.620 --> 00:57:03.640 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I'm all about
restoring our citizenship

00:57:03.640 --> 00:57:05.860 align:middle line:84%
and realizing that it's
not that we don't need

00:57:05.860 --> 00:57:09.230 align:middle line:84%
to buy food and clothing
and take care of ourselves,

00:57:09.230 --> 00:57:13.760 align:middle line:84%
but there is a kind of
mindset of never enough,

00:57:13.760 --> 00:57:15.770 align:middle line:84%
we've got to have
more, that there's not

00:57:15.770 --> 00:57:18.270 align:middle line:84%
enough to go around, you've got
to get yours before somebody

00:57:18.270 --> 00:57:21.380 align:middle line:84%
else gets it, that more
is better no matter what,

00:57:21.380 --> 00:57:25.120 align:middle line:84%
more shoes, more sweaters,
more market share, more houses,

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:27.470 align:middle line:84%
more square feet in your
house, more magazines,

00:57:27.470 --> 00:57:29.026 align:middle line:90%
more everything.

00:57:29.026 --> 00:57:30.650 align:middle line:84%
And that that's just
the way that it is

00:57:30.650 --> 00:57:32.524 align:middle line:84%
and that's the kind of
world we're living in.

00:57:32.524 --> 00:57:34.770 align:middle line:84%
When in fact, if you
really look at that

00:57:34.770 --> 00:57:37.120 align:middle line:84%
as an unconscious,
unexamined assumption,

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:40.170 align:middle line:84%
almost like an
obsession and addiction,

00:57:40.170 --> 00:57:44.982 align:middle line:84%
and you suspend it or bracket
it, if you will, for just--

00:57:44.982 --> 00:57:45.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A moment.

00:57:45.690 --> 00:57:47.520 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --even for
a moment and take

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:50.320 align:middle line:84%
a look at what
you actually have.

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:53.760 align:middle line:84%
The beauty of your friendships,
all the people that

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:58.740 align:middle line:84%
love you, the incredible gift of
health and well being, the fact

00:57:58.740 --> 00:58:01.450 align:middle line:84%
that you are fed, that you
are taken care of, that you

00:58:01.450 --> 00:58:03.640 align:middle line:84%
actually really do
have what you need.

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:07.820 align:middle line:84%
Now, maybe you want more of this
or more of that, but we're OK.

00:58:07.820 --> 00:58:10.544 align:middle line:84%
And there is a
wonderful-- there's

00:58:10.544 --> 00:58:11.960 align:middle line:84%
so many things to
say about this--

00:58:11.960 --> 00:58:15.200 align:middle line:84%
but there's a wonderful
teacher that I love so much,

00:58:15.200 --> 00:58:18.550 align:middle line:84%
Brother David Steindl-Rast,
who's one of my great teachers.

00:58:18.550 --> 00:58:21.760 align:middle line:84%
He's in his 80s now
and I was really

00:58:21.760 --> 00:58:23.970 align:middle line:84%
so blessed teach
with him many times.

00:58:23.970 --> 00:58:28.370 align:middle line:84%
And he says we're not
grateful because we're happy,

00:58:28.370 --> 00:58:31.240 align:middle line:84%
we're happy because
we're grateful.

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:34.227 align:middle line:84%
And he lives in a state
of absolute constant

00:58:34.227 --> 00:58:34.810 align:middle line:90%
gratefulness--

00:58:34.810 --> 00:58:35.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Gratitude.

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:38.000 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --which he
calls great fullness.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:38.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:58:38.900 --> 00:58:40.920 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: The great
fullness of life.

00:58:40.920 --> 00:58:46.230 align:middle line:84%
So I-- there's such
a rich treasure trove

00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:49.510 align:middle line:84%
of a conversation about
sufficiency or enough

00:58:49.510 --> 00:58:52.300 align:middle line:84%
that I love to engage
with with people.

00:58:52.300 --> 00:58:54.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But we are, though,
still in an economy.

00:58:54.910 --> 00:58:57.380 align:middle line:84%
The economy does make
this world go round,

00:58:57.380 --> 00:59:00.970 align:middle line:84%
it is a system that we
are currently a part of.

00:59:00.970 --> 00:59:03.550 align:middle line:84%
Maybe not so much the
indigenous cultures,

00:59:03.550 --> 00:59:05.700 align:middle line:84%
maybe they are still
in a place of being

00:59:05.700 --> 00:59:09.310 align:middle line:84%
able to trade and have
that type of associations.

00:59:09.310 --> 00:59:11.620 align:middle line:90%
But we are in this economy.

00:59:11.620 --> 00:59:13.300 align:middle line:90%
So how do you bridge that gap?

00:59:13.300 --> 00:59:14.440 align:middle line:90%
How do you narrow it?

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:16.410 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Well, it's
really challenging.

00:59:16.410 --> 00:59:17.490 align:middle line:90%
You're absolutely right.

00:59:17.490 --> 00:59:22.602 align:middle line:84%
We're in a system, a money
system, an economic system--

00:59:22.602 --> 00:59:24.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That isn't
working so well.

00:59:24.060 --> 00:59:24.720 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --that isn't
working so well.

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:25.803 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: According to some.

00:59:25.803 --> 00:59:28.430 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: That's not based
on any real value, that

00:59:28.430 --> 00:59:32.840 align:middle line:84%
generates a constant
demand for more.

00:59:32.840 --> 00:59:35.350 align:middle line:84%
In fact, even money
comes into existence

00:59:35.350 --> 00:59:36.530 align:middle line:90%
with interest attached.

00:59:36.530 --> 00:59:38.127 align:middle line:84%
The Federal Reserve
is a private bank,

00:59:38.127 --> 00:59:39.460 align:middle line:90%
it's not part of the government.

00:59:39.460 --> 00:59:40.830 align:middle line:90%
Most people don't know that.

00:59:40.830 --> 00:59:44.430 align:middle line:84%
And when money is issued, it's
issued with interest attached,

00:59:44.430 --> 00:59:45.750 align:middle line:90%
it needs to be paid back.

00:59:45.750 --> 00:59:50.250 align:middle line:84%
So there's always less money in
circulation than there is owed.

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:54.350 align:middle line:84%
So money itself, in the system
of money, generates debt.

00:59:54.350 --> 00:59:57.140 align:middle line:84%
That actually is the
money system that we have.

00:59:57.140 --> 01:00:00.270 align:middle line:84%
And the money system
itself creates

01:00:00.270 --> 01:00:04.210 align:middle line:84%
an imperative for growth because
the only way you can pay back

01:00:04.210 --> 01:00:07.460 align:middle line:84%
the interest-- which is more
money than is in circulation--

01:00:07.460 --> 01:00:09.450 align:middle line:90%
is by growing the economy.

01:00:09.450 --> 01:00:13.090 align:middle line:84%
And that means we have to
commodify more and more

01:00:13.090 --> 01:00:14.610 align:middle line:90%
and more of the natural world.

01:00:14.610 --> 01:00:18.330 align:middle line:84%
We need to consume it in order
to create a growing economy.

01:00:18.330 --> 01:00:22.240 align:middle line:84%
And that is a runaway
unconscious, unexamined

01:00:22.240 --> 01:00:24.140 align:middle line:84%
assumption that now
is being questioned

01:00:24.140 --> 01:00:28.140 align:middle line:84%
by some of the very most premier
economists on this planet.

01:00:28.140 --> 01:00:31.410 align:middle line:84%
Also, the money system itself
is being questioned in a way

01:00:31.410 --> 01:00:33.200 align:middle line:90%
that it never has been before.

01:00:33.200 --> 01:00:36.060 align:middle line:84%
So that's the blessing, I
say, of the financial crisis.

01:00:36.060 --> 01:00:39.659 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But how does that
tie into making a difference

01:00:39.659 --> 01:00:41.450 align:middle line:84%
and to the fundraising
that you talk about?

01:00:41.450 --> 01:00:44.360 align:middle line:84%
Because you really have a
wonderful different slant

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:45.160 align:middle line:90%
on fundraising.

01:00:45.160 --> 01:00:48.480 align:middle line:84%
When you have a mission
or a passion or something

01:00:48.480 --> 01:00:50.689 align:middle line:84%
that you want to do
to really help people

01:00:50.689 --> 01:00:52.230 align:middle line:84%
or to make a difference
in the world,

01:00:52.230 --> 01:00:54.730 align:middle line:84%
but you don't necessarily
have the means to be

01:00:54.730 --> 01:00:58.340 align:middle line:84%
able to make that difference
because it requires finances.

01:00:58.340 --> 01:01:00.710 align:middle line:84%
Yet, you can get those
finances because we

01:01:00.710 --> 01:01:02.600 align:middle line:90%
are in an economic system.

01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:05.810 align:middle line:84%
How do you bridge
all of that together?

01:01:05.810 --> 01:01:07.530 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Well, wow.

01:01:07.530 --> 01:01:09.895 align:middle line:90%
That's a wonderful big question.

01:01:09.895 --> 01:01:10.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

01:01:10.910 --> 01:01:11.835 align:middle line:90%
It's a big one.

01:01:11.835 --> 01:01:13.210 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: If I'm
not careful, I'll

01:01:13.210 --> 01:01:16.860 align:middle line:84%
push B7 and start my whole
workshop with you here.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:19.800 align:middle line:84%
But I actually have
learned almost everything

01:01:19.800 --> 01:01:21.510 align:middle line:84%
I know about money
from raising money.

01:01:21.510 --> 01:01:23.550 align:middle line:84%
I've raised hundreds
and hundreds of millions

01:01:23.550 --> 01:01:25.799 align:middle line:84%
of dollars, I've trained
somewhere in the neighborhood

01:01:25.799 --> 01:01:28.420 align:middle line:84%
of 50,000 fundraisers
in something

01:01:28.420 --> 01:01:30.410 align:middle line:90%
like 50, 60 countries.

01:01:30.410 --> 01:01:33.780 align:middle line:84%
I've trained people in Ethiopia
to raise money from each other.

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:35.530 align:middle line:84%
One of the poorest
countries in the world.

01:01:35.530 --> 01:01:39.390 align:middle line:84%
Or Bangladesh or
even Mozambique.

01:01:39.390 --> 01:01:43.785 align:middle line:84%
And I have learned
that if really you

01:01:43.785 --> 01:01:46.010 align:middle line:84%
see fundraising in
a different light.

01:01:46.010 --> 01:01:50.330 align:middle line:84%
So it's so hard to give you
enough of a download about this

01:01:50.330 --> 01:01:53.700 align:middle line:84%
without doing the whole
workshop, but I'll say that--

01:01:53.700 --> 01:01:57.070 align:middle line:84%
or reading the whole book-- I'll
say that I learned a lot of it

01:01:57.070 --> 01:01:58.120 align:middle line:90%
in the Hunger Project.

01:01:58.120 --> 01:01:59.750 align:middle line:84%
And the Hunger
Project is dedicated

01:01:59.750 --> 01:02:01.420 align:middle line:84%
to really eradicating
world hunger.

01:02:01.420 --> 01:02:03.450 align:middle line:90%
Eradicating it.

01:02:03.450 --> 01:02:07.354 align:middle line:84%
And so we obviously needed to
raise a little money to even--

01:02:07.354 --> 01:02:08.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a big--

01:02:08.270 --> 01:02:08.800 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: --do that kind of work.

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:09.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --project.

01:02:09.210 --> 01:02:09.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:02:09.720 --> 01:02:11.970 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And from
the very outset,

01:02:11.970 --> 01:02:14.460 align:middle line:84%
we saw that many
organizations were

01:02:14.460 --> 01:02:18.320 align:middle line:84%
using the pornography of
poverty to make people feel

01:02:18.320 --> 01:02:21.530 align:middle line:84%
guilty and bad so that they
would dig into their pocket

01:02:21.530 --> 01:02:22.230 align:middle line:90%
and give money.

01:02:22.230 --> 01:02:24.620 align:middle line:84%
And then you need to
have the hungry people

01:02:24.620 --> 01:02:26.690 align:middle line:90%
to keep your organization going.

01:02:26.690 --> 01:02:28.640 align:middle line:84%
So it actually is
a self-defeating--

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:29.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

01:02:29.140 --> 01:02:30.360 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: --system.

01:02:30.360 --> 01:02:32.220 align:middle line:90%
It also is undignified.

01:02:32.220 --> 01:02:35.180 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't really
raise up who they are.

01:02:35.180 --> 01:02:39.660 align:middle line:84%
And so I've really, really--
I'm kind of a poster girl

01:02:39.660 --> 01:02:43.350 align:middle line:84%
for that-- we used to say
in the Hunger Project,

01:02:43.350 --> 01:02:46.160 align:middle line:84%
there's not a billion
mouths to feed.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:48.210 align:middle line:84%
There's a billion
people standing

01:02:48.210 --> 01:02:50.500 align:middle line:84%
on the front lines of
ending world hunger, some

01:02:50.500 --> 01:02:54.680 align:middle line:84%
of the most courageous,
innovative, intelligent,

01:02:54.680 --> 01:02:57.280 align:middle line:90%
amazing people in the world.

01:02:57.280 --> 01:02:59.140 align:middle line:84%
And we have the
privilege-- and they're

01:02:59.140 --> 01:03:01.480 align:middle line:84%
the people who
experience hunger--

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:03.870 align:middle line:84%
and we have the
privilege to join them.

01:03:03.870 --> 01:03:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And so rather than see them
as somebody we feel sorry for,

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:10.670 align:middle line:84%
if you see the-- if you've
worked them the way I have,

01:03:10.670 --> 01:03:12.336 align:middle line:84%
people live in those
conditions, I mean,

01:03:12.336 --> 01:03:14.940 align:middle line:84%
you wouldn't believe what a
woman does when she has seven

01:03:14.940 --> 01:03:17.250 align:middle line:84%
children, her husband's
abandoned her,

01:03:17.250 --> 01:03:18.710 align:middle line:90%
she doesn't have any food.

01:03:18.710 --> 01:03:20.840 align:middle line:84%
How is she going to
get through the day?

01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:22.010 align:middle line:90%
You think about that.

01:03:22.010 --> 01:03:22.510 align:middle line:90%
You've got a daughter.

01:03:22.510 --> 01:03:23.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: For a minute.

01:03:23.170 --> 01:03:23.370 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:03:23.370 --> 01:03:23.550 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:03:23.550 --> 01:03:25.008 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: You just
think about that.

01:03:25.008 --> 01:03:29.460 align:middle line:84%
I've sat with women in Ethiopia
after every single child

01:03:29.460 --> 01:03:32.755 align:middle line:84%
that they had died in famine and
they were motherless-- sorry.

01:03:32.755 --> 01:03:33.505 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Childless.

01:03:33.505 --> 01:03:34.880 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Childless mothers.

01:03:34.880 --> 01:03:35.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

01:03:35.740 --> 01:03:39.900 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And seeing what
that does to a woman

01:03:39.900 --> 01:03:42.020 align:middle line:84%
to lose her own child and
not be able to feed her

01:03:42.020 --> 01:03:45.230 align:middle line:84%
even if she has a baby at her
breast and there's no more milk

01:03:45.230 --> 01:03:48.120 align:middle line:84%
because she hasn't had
water in two weeks.

01:03:48.120 --> 01:03:49.020 align:middle line:90%
You know?

01:03:49.020 --> 01:03:50.780 align:middle line:90%
These are courageous people.

01:03:50.780 --> 01:03:52.780 align:middle line:84%
They may not know
how to read, they

01:03:52.780 --> 01:03:58.310 align:middle line:84%
may be uneducated or illiterate,
but they're not unintelligent.

01:03:58.310 --> 01:04:00.810 align:middle line:84%
And I can even tell
you, those same women

01:04:00.810 --> 01:04:03.720 align:middle line:84%
that I sat with in
Ethiopia and mourned

01:04:03.720 --> 01:04:05.140 align:middle line:84%
over the deaths
of their children

01:04:05.140 --> 01:04:08.460 align:middle line:84%
when they described each
excruciating death-- now,

01:04:08.460 --> 01:04:11.820 align:middle line:84%
out of the seven that I sat
with for five days and five

01:04:11.820 --> 01:04:13.530 align:middle line:84%
nights, four of
them-- who had never

01:04:13.530 --> 01:04:17.500 align:middle line:84%
even knew how to read or write,
and they were in their late 40s

01:04:17.500 --> 01:04:21.100 align:middle line:84%
when this famine took place
in Ethiopia back in 1984,

01:04:21.100 --> 01:04:26.090 align:middle line:84%
1985-- four of them have gone
all the way through school,

01:04:26.090 --> 01:04:28.580 align:middle line:84%
three of them have
PhD's and one of them

01:04:28.580 --> 01:04:31.940 align:middle line:84%
is a lawyer and running
the largest female law

01:04:31.940 --> 01:04:33.340 align:middle line:90%
firm in Ethiopia.

01:04:33.340 --> 01:04:36.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We actually have picture
of some of these experiences

01:04:36.580 --> 01:04:37.430 align:middle line:90%
that you've been on.

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:39.182 align:middle line:84%
And I want to also
close the loop on what

01:04:39.182 --> 01:04:40.890 align:middle line:84%
we were talking about
about the finances.

01:04:40.890 --> 01:04:44.300 align:middle line:84%
But to give people a
visual of where you've been

01:04:44.300 --> 01:04:46.930 align:middle line:84%
and where your journeys have
taken you and the impact

01:04:46.930 --> 01:04:48.880 align:middle line:84%
that you've made
around the globe

01:04:48.880 --> 01:04:51.250 align:middle line:90%
is really-- it's worth sharing.

01:04:51.250 --> 01:04:54.880 align:middle line:84%
This particular
picture is of a school.

01:04:54.880 --> 01:04:57.539 align:middle line:90%
Did you help create this school?

01:04:57.539 --> 01:04:59.830 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Well, that's actually
not a school we created,

01:04:59.830 --> 01:05:03.450 align:middle line:84%
but we created a literacy
program in that school

01:05:03.450 --> 01:05:04.800 align:middle line:90%
specifically for girls.

01:05:04.800 --> 01:05:08.370 align:middle line:84%
Because in much of Asia
and sub-Saharan Africa,

01:05:08.370 --> 01:05:11.500 align:middle line:84%
girls aren't valued and they
don't get to go to school.

01:05:11.500 --> 01:05:16.110 align:middle line:84%
And an educated girl changes
the picture dramatically.

01:05:16.110 --> 01:05:19.360 align:middle line:84%
They have fewer children, they
don't get married so early,

01:05:19.360 --> 01:05:21.010 align:middle line:84%
they say in Africa,
if you educate

01:05:21.010 --> 01:05:25.300 align:middle line:84%
a man you educate one person, if
you educate a girl or a woman,

01:05:25.300 --> 01:05:26.312 align:middle line:90%
you educate a nation.

01:05:26.312 --> 01:05:27.520 align:middle line:90%
And it's really, really true.

01:05:27.520 --> 01:05:28.020 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

01:05:28.020 --> 01:05:31.670 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: So that is a scene
from a school where we opened up

01:05:31.670 --> 01:05:33.820 align:middle line:84%
the whole possibility
of educating girls

01:05:33.820 --> 01:05:37.340 align:middle line:84%
and ran a literacy clinic
focused on boys and girls.

01:05:37.340 --> 01:05:40.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So that really does
also impact the world hunger

01:05:40.090 --> 01:05:41.609 align:middle line:90%
and the Hunger Project as well.

01:05:41.609 --> 01:05:42.150 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yes.

01:05:42.150 --> 01:05:42.515 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:05:42.515 --> 01:05:43.150 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

01:05:43.150 --> 01:05:46.120 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And this is with you
and President Bill Clinton.

01:05:46.120 --> 01:05:49.180 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: And that's Joan
Holmes who was for many years

01:05:49.180 --> 01:05:51.520 align:middle line:84%
the president of the Hunger
Project and my great mentor

01:05:51.520 --> 01:05:52.600 align:middle line:90%
and teacher.

01:05:52.600 --> 01:05:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And that's in Washington
when we gave the Africa

01:05:56.260 --> 01:05:58.820 align:middle line:84%
Prize for leadership-- a
prize the Hunger Project gives

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:02.900 align:middle line:84%
each year-- to Nelson
Mandela for his great work.

01:06:02.900 --> 01:06:05.630 align:middle line:84%
President Clinton was president
at that time, so he came.

01:06:05.630 --> 01:06:06.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

01:06:06.540 --> 01:06:07.760 align:middle line:90%
He came for our party.

01:06:07.760 --> 01:06:10.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Dignitaries
to now children in--

01:06:10.400 --> 01:06:11.970 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: That's in Senegal.

01:06:11.970 --> 01:06:16.860 align:middle line:84%
I worked very much
in the Sahel Desert

01:06:16.860 --> 01:06:20.850 align:middle line:84%
where there's all kinds of
people living where there's not

01:06:20.850 --> 01:06:24.250 align:middle line:84%
a blade of grass and where you
don't think there's any water.

01:06:24.250 --> 01:06:27.604 align:middle line:84%
But we discovered, the
women actually discovered,

01:06:27.604 --> 01:06:29.020 align:middle line:84%
that if they dug
deep enough there

01:06:29.020 --> 01:06:31.960 align:middle line:84%
was an underground lake
under all of 17 villages.

01:06:31.960 --> 01:06:34.111 align:middle line:84%
75,000 people were
saved from starvation.

01:06:34.111 --> 01:06:34.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

01:06:34.610 --> 01:06:35.570 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Because
women's intuition

01:06:35.570 --> 01:06:37.020 align:middle line:84%
knew that there
was a well there.

01:06:37.020 --> 01:06:40.110 align:middle line:84%
And that's a scene
from the village

01:06:40.110 --> 01:06:41.710 align:middle line:90%
in that region of the Sahel.

01:06:41.710 --> 01:06:42.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, my goodness.

01:06:42.710 --> 01:06:43.910 align:middle line:90%
Look at how happy you are.

01:06:43.910 --> 01:06:44.520 align:middle line:90%
You just--

01:06:44.520 --> 01:06:44.950 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: I'm so happy.

01:06:44.950 --> 01:06:45.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You glow.

01:06:45.750 --> 01:06:48.840 align:middle line:84%
Look at-- I mean, this is a
picture of a woman on purpose.

01:06:48.840 --> 01:06:49.890 align:middle line:90%
That's beautiful.

01:06:49.890 --> 01:06:51.390 align:middle line:90%
And--

01:06:51.390 --> 01:06:54.620 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: That's in India at
Mother Teresa's orphanage

01:06:54.620 --> 01:06:56.760 align:middle line:90%
in Calcutta.

01:06:56.760 --> 01:06:58.800 align:middle line:84%
Mother Teresa was
another teacher for me.

01:06:58.800 --> 01:07:04.900 align:middle line:84%
I can't believe I even got
a chance to kiss her hand.

01:07:04.900 --> 01:07:08.520 align:middle line:84%
But I really learned so
much from Mother Teresa.

01:07:08.520 --> 01:07:10.940 align:middle line:84%
She actually was a great
fundraiser, by the way.

01:07:10.940 --> 01:07:14.350 align:middle line:84%
And so I had a lot of work I
did in India for the Hunger

01:07:14.350 --> 01:07:17.510 align:middle line:84%
Project, gave me access, and
kind of the great privilege

01:07:17.510 --> 01:07:19.750 align:middle line:84%
of working with her and
really learning from her

01:07:19.750 --> 01:07:21.480 align:middle line:84%
and knowing her before
she passed away.

01:07:21.480 --> 01:07:23.940 align:middle line:84%
So that's in one
of her orphanages.

01:07:23.940 --> 01:07:25.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And there she is.

01:07:25.170 --> 01:07:26.086 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: There she is.

01:07:26.086 --> 01:07:29.180 align:middle line:84%
She's signing her
business card which

01:07:29.180 --> 01:07:31.940 align:middle line:84%
has got the Saint Francis
of Assisi prayer on it.

01:07:31.940 --> 01:07:35.132 align:middle line:90%
And then she signs it M.Teresa.

01:07:35.132 --> 01:07:38.019 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: M. Short for mother.

01:07:38.019 --> 01:07:38.602 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

01:07:38.602 --> 01:07:40.810 align:middle line:90%
Short for mother.

01:07:40.810 --> 01:07:44.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: M period earth.

01:07:44.250 --> 01:07:46.110 align:middle line:90%
That's-- wow.

01:07:46.110 --> 01:07:50.707 align:middle line:84%
She's-- I want to hear a little
bit more about her fundraising

01:07:50.707 --> 01:07:51.540 align:middle line:90%
and how she does it.

01:07:51.540 --> 01:07:52.248 align:middle line:90%
And where's this?

01:07:52.248 --> 01:07:54.310 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: That's in Bangladesh.

01:07:54.310 --> 01:07:58.290 align:middle line:84%
Bangladesh is one of my--
I love all these places,

01:07:58.290 --> 01:07:59.200 align:middle line:90%
I love Bangladesh.

01:07:59.200 --> 01:08:02.680 align:middle line:84%
Bangladesh has 140 million
people living in a land mass

01:08:02.680 --> 01:08:03.710 align:middle line:90%
the size of Iowa.

01:08:03.710 --> 01:08:07.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is one of the
most sparse rural areas

01:08:07.020 --> 01:08:08.010 align:middle line:90%
in Bangladesh.

01:08:08.010 --> 01:08:10.209 align:middle line:84%
But you can see, even
there, they build the houses

01:08:10.209 --> 01:08:11.750 align:middle line:84%
right next to each
other because it's

01:08:11.750 --> 01:08:14.810 align:middle line:84%
a very densely populated
kind of mindset.

01:08:14.810 --> 01:08:16.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But look at how
they've build the houses.

01:08:16.930 --> 01:08:20.830 align:middle line:84%
Those are made out of the
local environment, of course,

01:08:20.830 --> 01:08:24.914 align:middle line:84%
and provide shelter and
they're very, very sturdy.

01:08:24.914 --> 01:08:25.830 align:middle line:90%
They look very sturdy.

01:08:25.830 --> 01:08:26.390 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Yeah.

01:08:26.390 --> 01:08:26.779 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:08:26.779 --> 01:08:28.279 align:middle line:84%
It's a wonderful,
wonderful country.

01:08:28.279 --> 01:08:32.260 align:middle line:84%
And Bangladeshi people, their
primary art form is poetry.

01:08:32.260 --> 01:08:34.970 align:middle line:84%
And they are
extraordinary poets.

01:08:34.970 --> 01:08:37.779 align:middle line:84%
You don't think of Bangladesh
as a country of poets,

01:08:37.779 --> 01:08:40.326 align:middle line:84%
but I want to say
that so people know.

01:08:40.326 --> 01:08:42.040 align:middle line:84%
Going to Bangladesh
is an experience

01:08:42.040 --> 01:08:45.320 align:middle line:84%
of interacting with profound--
a profound love for poetry.

01:08:45.320 --> 01:08:46.695 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you
get to experience

01:08:46.695 --> 01:08:47.710 align:middle line:90%
some of the readings?

01:08:47.710 --> 01:08:48.460 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: Oh, yeah.

01:08:48.460 --> 01:08:48.960 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:51.564 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What are they about?

01:08:51.564 --> 01:08:55.120 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Very much about their
own love for life and love

01:08:55.120 --> 01:09:00.180 align:middle line:84%
for-- they have constant
tsunamis and floods

01:09:00.180 --> 01:09:02.840 align:middle line:84%
and they rebuild their houses
every 10 minutes because they

01:09:02.840 --> 01:09:04.729 align:middle line:84%
get flooded, it's in
a low land, and it's

01:09:04.729 --> 01:09:07.500 align:middle line:84%
one of the countries that
will absolutely disappear

01:09:07.500 --> 01:09:11.920 align:middle line:84%
with global warming
if the oceans rise.

01:09:11.920 --> 01:09:14.930 align:middle line:84%
And so there is a resilience
in the Bangladeshi people

01:09:14.930 --> 01:09:18.250 align:middle line:84%
that they-- that
they sing about.

01:09:18.250 --> 01:09:20.200 align:middle line:84%
They also do
fantastic embroidery.

01:09:20.200 --> 01:09:22.890 align:middle line:84%
And that's where the
Grameen Bank was born.

01:09:22.890 --> 01:09:24.734 align:middle line:84%
The microcredit
movement really--

01:09:24.734 --> 01:09:25.359 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

01:09:25.359 --> 01:09:27.442 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: -- you could say
was born in many places,

01:09:27.442 --> 01:09:31.040 align:middle line:84%
but Muhammad Yunus, who
won the Nobel Prize, Dr.

01:09:31.040 --> 01:09:33.750 align:middle line:84%
Muhammad Yunus who started the
Grameen Bank the same year we

01:09:33.750 --> 01:09:36.610 align:middle line:84%
started the Hunger
Project-- 1977.

01:09:36.610 --> 01:09:38.109 align:middle line:84%
And we worked very
closely with him.

01:09:38.109 --> 01:09:42.700 align:middle line:84%
And that's a bank
that is owned by women

01:09:42.700 --> 01:09:47.970 align:middle line:84%
and lends primarily to
women, $25, $50, $75.

01:09:47.970 --> 01:09:50.430 align:middle line:84%
It's the beginning of
the microcredit movement.

01:09:50.430 --> 01:09:53.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's an
amazing movement as well.

01:09:53.560 --> 01:09:55.689 align:middle line:84%
And then this is the women
you were speaking of.

01:09:55.689 --> 01:09:56.730 align:middle line:90%
>>TWIST: That's in Ghana.

01:09:56.730 --> 01:09:57.688 align:middle line:90%
That's not in Ethiopia.

01:09:57.688 --> 01:09:58.880 align:middle line:90%
That's in Ghana.

01:09:58.880 --> 01:10:03.350 align:middle line:84%
And those women are part of
also Women's World Banking which

01:10:03.350 --> 01:10:05.490 align:middle line:84%
is another microcredit
movement that--

01:10:05.490 --> 01:10:06.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

01:10:06.080 --> 01:10:08.600 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: --was founded
by many different people,

01:10:08.600 --> 01:10:11.950 align:middle line:84%
but one of the founders
is Esther Ocloo in Ghana.

01:10:11.950 --> 01:10:15.040 align:middle line:84%
And that's at her
center where these

01:10:15.040 --> 01:10:16.940 align:middle line:84%
are women who are
learning about banking

01:10:16.940 --> 01:10:20.290 align:middle line:84%
and learning about how to
navigate the world of money.

01:10:20.290 --> 01:10:22.757 align:middle line:90%
And just a wonderful place.

01:10:22.757 --> 01:10:24.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So we were
talking about that,

01:10:24.340 --> 01:10:27.530 align:middle line:84%
and I had asked you about
how the fundraising and how

01:10:27.530 --> 01:10:32.500 align:middle line:84%
you teach people that are in--
even in countries that don't

01:10:32.500 --> 01:10:34.620 align:middle line:84%
have access to a lot of
money, you teach them

01:10:34.620 --> 01:10:38.750 align:middle line:84%
how to raise funds
amongst themselves.

01:10:38.750 --> 01:10:40.416 align:middle line:90%
How do you do that?

01:10:40.416 --> 01:10:43.970 align:middle line:84%
>>TWIST: Well, I
just must say that we

01:10:43.970 --> 01:10:48.450 align:middle line:84%
think of fundraising as
haves giving to have nots.

01:10:48.450 --> 01:10:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And I try to do everything
I can to sort break up

01:10:52.010 --> 01:10:53.120 align:middle line:90%
our thinking about that.

01:10:53.120 --> 01:10:56.730 align:middle line:84%
Because in the way
I see it, this world

01:10:56.730 --> 01:10:59.660 align:middle line:84%
of sufficiency and
enough, which is really

01:10:59.660 --> 01:11:02.130 align:middle line:84%
how I see the world, really
thanks to Buckminster

01:11:02.130 --> 01:11:04.900 align:middle line:84%
Fuller-- and I could
tell you about that, too.

01:11:04.900 --> 01:11:06.720 align:middle line:90%
I see that everybody's a have.

01:11:06.720 --> 01:11:08.350 align:middle line:90%
There aren't any have nots.

01:11:08.350 --> 01:11:14.410 align:middle line:84%
So in a place like-- you
